#10020
The Old Growth~
The heart of the ancient forest opens in a space so vast and cathedral-like that the eye struggles to reckon the scale; trees of immeasurable age rise into darkness above, their trunks forming columns of a natural temple.
The forest floor stretches away in every direction with an invitation that feels both genuine and predatory, the paths leading deeper into something that has been watchful and patient since long before the coming of civilization.
No wind moves here, and yet the canopy far above sways in slow, complex arcs that suggest not a breeze but the slow breathing of the forest itself, each cycle taking minutes to complete.
The silence is structural rather than circumstantial, built into the space by centuries of growth toward a specific acoustic end -- a silence that listens as much as it is listened to.
To the north, the mossy archway of intertwined roots frames the return passage like a door that the forest has always intended to keep open, its living gate the only seam between this place and the world beyond.
~
